<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">I have to disagree with some of your points Dune.  I would agree that the Ogre is probably the best stat and ability based SK for groups in general.  But to me it sounds like you play a Sk because you wanted a warrior with some spells.  Well I've seen many players who thought this way and I never felt that they work as efficently soloing or in a group as people who don't think of themselves as a warrior with some spells.  Sks take a big AC/damage/HP deficite to get their spells.  If you are just going to be a warrior in your group (who casts an occasional darkness)then they might as well take a warrior.  We are tanks and can replace warriors in groups but it takes a little more than pressing the taunt and slam buttons every few seconds.  Sks are one of the better tanks at taunting, they can outdamage a warrior without HT if they are willing to sacrifice the mana on that fight, they have excelent pulling tools, from my experience they can fear kite even mobs past 40 without too much trouble.  Some resists or early breaks in the spells will give some downtime trying to get back those HPs but it can be safely done.  Try the Giants in BW.  At 49 invoke fear will help the resists as well.  And if your a Sk and afraid to touch something a warrior isn't then you're a pansy SK.  I love warriors and have many good friends who play them as their main.  They are better in many situations than a SK but I've yet to see a mob that a warrior could solo that a SK couldn't even without any fearing (assuming simialar equipment for the level).  Sure if you go into fights not casting then you are just a weak warrior and I'd be afraid too.  But when your spells are used properly you can do so much more.  And I;ve had many times where I'd trade my HPs for mana.  40 mana for a fear can save 100's of Hps.  Or 100 mana for a darkness keeps the opponent from running.  Or 60 mana for a FD or even 10 for a shadow step.  Those HPs wouldn't have run me to the zone in time or let me melee longer...  <p>

But anyway this is supposed to be about HT vs LoH.  I've already posted my comments about that but thought I should say the above because I think Dune is wrong on a few points and want people to see another opinion so they can see both sides and figure it out themselves.</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
